Police said they were called to Grazebrook Croft in the Bartley Green suburb of the city at 11.20am on Friday. The victim, who is believed to be in his early 50s, sadly died at the scene. West Midlands Police said they do not know why the man was attacked and searches are underway for the culprit. Detectives have been carrying out door to door enquiries in the neighbourhood and scouring CCTV for any clues. A police drone has also been capturing images to help with the probe. Specialist teams have also joined forensic experts as they search for evidence. Grazebrook Croft and nearby Bigwood Drive were closed by West Midlands Police whose spokesperson said they will remain cordoned off until at least Saturday. He added that people living in the roads will be allowed into or out of their homes, but they will be disrupted and may need to wait to be escorted though the area. Officers were working to identify the victims so they could tell his family the sad news. A West Midlands Ambulance Service spokeswoman said it was called at 11.16am to reports of a stabbing in Birmingham.   READ MORE ABOUT A LIST OF 'PROBABLE' NUCLEAR TARGETS IN THE UK She added: "Upon arrival we found an elderly man. "He was assessed and had sustained life threatening injuries. He received advanced trauma care from ambulance staff on scene. "Unfortunately, despite their best efforts, it became clear that nothing more could be done to save him and he was confirmed deceased at the scene."  DON'T MISS: Sky News reporter takes on Lavrov over hospital tragedy [REPORT] Princess Diana’s wedding dress designer was ‘HORRIFIED’ by gown [REVEALED] Royal Family LIVE: Harry & Meghan savaged for new political move [LATEST]  Anyone with information about the attack should contact police by calling 101 quoting incident number 1483-110322. Information can also be given anonymously by calling Crimestoppers on 0800 555 111. You may be entitled to a reward, even if you choose to stay anonymous. 